Apologies I forgot to add case notes at the analysis stage. 
Although the right hand side of this mark is very unclear and dark, I can see the pattern clearly. The minutiae visible on the left hand side are clear and without distortion. The form doesn't disclose some of the minutiae on the left hand side.

Degree of similarity: 3

Degree of support: 4

There is a line of distortion that runs diagonally from 11 o'clock to 5 o'clock from the core following the 3 Difference indicator stars. This line appears to alter ridge detail along that orientation and adds an additional ridge ending (3).

Degree of similarity: 4
Degree of support: 4

Medium degree of similarity including consideration of ridge flow and shape.

Some of the the differences are within a very dark, heavy deposition area of the mark. I don't have high confidence in all of the minutiae due to poor clarity. 

I was  swaying between identification and inconclusive but don't feel comfortable with identification. 

Support for inconclusive

Degree of Similarity - 4 - high level of correspondence. If mark had not been subject to the pressure distortion and detail obliterated this may have been a 5 with the greater number of features available for comparison.

Mark identified to reference print. I have highlighted a difference above core but this may be due to the deposition pressure obscuring the characteristics. Form is not captured well but enough characteristics to make an identification. Small lake added as characteristic in mark

degree of similarity 4

degree of support 4

I feel this pattern has a medium level of discriminability , although there are a few features around the core there is nothing in particular that I would say is out with the norm and this looks like a very common average whorl pattern.
Pattern and ridge flow display a high degree of similarity and have established a high level of support for identification using the second level detail.

Full consensus.
